# Free City of Haven
--- start-multi-column: MainBody
```column-settings  
number of columns: 2  
column size: [69%, 30%]
border: [off]
shadow: off
```
At the north end of [[settlement/Trade Island|Trade Island]] stands a strong citadel, guarding the Long Road, the main east-west passage of trade since the beginnings of the [[organization/Namori Empire|Namori Empire]] some 2,000 years past. The [[organization/Citadel Guard|Citadel Guard]] has held to its duties for nearly that long.

Haven itself began as a small collection of huts on the south side of the river two and a half millennia ago and has risen and fallen many times (the ruins at the southern tip of the island date from about 1,500 years past), sometimes expanding, sometimes contracting. 

Because of the availability of good communications via the Long Road or the Dorian, Haven is a natural political center and has grown to be a thriving nexus of trade government and manufacturing.

Presently, Haven is of reasonably large size (there are 80,000 stories in the naked city) and sits squarely across the Long Road on both banks of the Dorian. Within the city's walls are a multitude of shops, residences, taverns, warehouses, and of course, people. 

About 175 years ago, economic necessity and pressure from the growing trades forced what little was left of the [[organization/Namori Empire|Namori Empire]] to grant a charter to the city, making it an independent political entity ruled by a Duke and providing more power to the people by way of an elected [[Organization/Government of Haven#Council of Boroughs|Council of Boroughs]].  Among other rights and privileges secured by this document was the freedom of the slaves, along with a recognition that slavery, per se, would never be permitted within the city again; indenturing, however, is not uncommon and is sometimes the only recourse a debtor has to avoid prison. 

Since that time the merchant class has steadily grown and some noble families were forced into selling off their lands to satisfy their creditors (the cannier members of the various trade Guilds). Today there are several wealthy merchant families and well-off individuals ... and far fewer noble families. This has led to a certain amount of rivalry between the nobility and the nouveau riche for the Duke's ear.

There are myriads of opportunities for a single person or for almost any group of adventurers - all they need to do is enter "THE FREE CITY OF HAVEN" and look for them

![[~attachments/DnDLine.png]]

# Demographics
Haven has grown to be a thriving nexus of trade government and manufacturing, with a population of almost 80,000. The traveler will find that most racces of Antheros can be found living here. While most of the population  are humans, there are Elves, Halflings, Dwarves, Centaurs, Half-orcs, Tieflings, and even the occasional [[Race/Avanthar|Avanthar]], Goliath, Pixie, Goblin, or [[species/Troll|Troll]] living in relative harmony. 

It is a polyglot city, a world of many colors, many languages, and many lifestyles. There are scholars and businessmen, priests and courtesans, fighters and thieves and mages - the city throbs day and night with the pulse and breath of adventure. 

![[~attachments/DnDLine.png]]

